We’re honoured to have received the National Award for our livelihood program for persons with disabilities by the Hon’ble President of India, Smt. Droupadi Murmu, today.

This recognition is a reflection of the passion, dedication, and hard work of every single person at Zomato who has helped make this program a success. Over the past two years, we’ve made real strides through these initiatives, and we couldn’t be prouder of what our teams have achieved together. Grateful to our partner @neomotionlife, for creating life transformative products for individuals with disabilities!

Looking ahead, we’re going to work towards onboarding over 5,000 individuals with disabilities into the Zomato team.

Our Founder & CEO, @deepigoyal has also made a pledge to support the education of children of delivery partners with disabilities, with the aim of creating a program that helps them achieve their dreams and build a brighter future. This recognition is our small step towards contributing to a more equitable society.

We have noticed social media conversations around single-dish restaurants listed on Zomato.

We have identified all such restaurants that were potentially fraudulent and have delisted them from our platform. To solve this more comprehensively, we have also investigated all other restaurants which have a very limited menu on Zomato and might have listed prohibited items or worked around a way to list prohibited items.

As per our policy, all restaurants listed on Zomato need to have a FSSAI license and we also actively block items such as alcohol, cigarettes/cigars/vapes from being listed on our platform. However, the restaurants highlighted were able to game our checks by using generic food names such as, ‘Naughty strawberry’, ‘Merry Berry’.

We have further strengthened our fraud checks to proactively identify such cases to avoid similar incidents in the future.

Recent articles around one of our delivery partners from Meerut earning ₹300 for working more than 6 hours on the day of Diwali were inaccurate and disturbing to us. Our delivery partners are at the heart of our service and we make sure we offer them with great earning opportunities to appreciate their hard-work and dedication, especially during festivals. 

Here are the facts -

The said delivery partner worked for 6hrs on 30th Oct (he did not login on the day of Diwali, as mentioned in the news articles)
He delivered 10 orders and cumulatively earned ₹695 
On the same day, a lot of delivery partners who devoted an average 10 hours in Meerut, cumulatively earned in the range of ₹1200 - ₹1300 

Misreported figures and narratives can impact livelihood, motivation, and dignity of individuals working in these roles. We request everyone to avoid spreading misinformation.
